## Appendix A: Mathematical Derivations

### A.1 Derivation of Bond Pricing Formula

Starting from no-arbitrage principle:

```
Bond Price = E^Q[Discounted Cash Flows]
```

Under risk-neutral measure Q:

For a coupon payment c/f at time tᵢ:
```
PV(coupon at tᵢ) = E^Q[Discount × Coupon × 𝟙{τ > tᵢ}]
                 = B(tᵢ) × (c/f) × Q(tᵢ)
```

For principal 100 at maturity T:
```
PV(principal) = E^Q[Discount × Principal × 𝟙{τ > T}]
              = B(T) × 100 × Q(T)
```

For recovery ℜ × 100 at default time τ:
```
PV(recovery) = E^Q[Discount(τ) × ℜ × 100 × 𝟙{τ ≤ T}]
             = ∫₀ᵀ B(t) × ℜ × 100 × dF(t)
             = ℜ × 100 × ∫₀ᵀ B(t) × [-dQ(t)]
             = ℜ × 100 × Ξ(T)
```

where F(t) = 1 - Q(t) is the cumulative distribution of τ.

**Total price:**
```
P = Σᵢ (c/f) B(tᵢ)Q(tᵢ) + 100 B(T)Q(T) + ℜ × 100 × Ξ(T)
```

### A.2 Derivation of Parity Equation

Consider a zero-coupon bond with face value 1:

```
Price = B(T)Q(T) + ℜ Ξ(T)
```

Now consider a portfolio paying $1/year continuously:

```
Portfolio value = ∫₀ᵀ B(t)Q(t)dt = Π(T)
```

This portfolio earns interest at the risky-weighted forward rate:

```
Interest earned = r_b(T) × Π(T)
```

By no-arbitrage, at t=0 investing in the portfolio must equal 1:

```
Portfolio cost + Interest = Final payout
Π(T) - r_b(T)Π(T) + [B(T)Q(T) + ℜΞ(T)] = 1

Rearranging:
B(T)Q(T) + Ξ(T) + r_b(T)Π(T) = 1
```

This is the fundamental parity equation.

